{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17652529","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17652529"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:37:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:37:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18538"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18538"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11270"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75593"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11270","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11270"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18538"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61111"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2305"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"7682"},{"type":"tags","id":"10863"},{"type":"tags","id":"10865"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26134"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26142"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75593"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA microbiologist is examining a cerebrospinal fluid sample from an immunocompromised patient under the microscope using India ink staining.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the microscopic appearance of Cryptococcus neoformans using this technique?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Branching filamentous hyphae","Large spherical cells with endospores","Small oval yeast cells in chains","Small budding yeast cells with clear surrounding halo","Elongated pseudohyphae with septations"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECryptococcus neoformans \u003C/em\u003Eis an encapsulated yeast that primarily infects immunocompromised patients. \u003Cstrong\u003ESmall budding yeast cells with clear surrounding halo\u003C/strong\u003E is the characteristic appearance of \u003Cem\u003ECryptococcus neoformans\u003C/em\u003E when viewed with India ink staining. The clear halo represents the polysaccharide capsule, which appears as a clear zone around the yeast cell as it displaces the dark India ink particles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent other fungal morphologies:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElongated pseudohyphae with septations\u003C/strong\u003E - This is typical of \u003Cem\u003ECandida\u003C/em\u003E species\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELarge spherical cells with endospores\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the appearance of \u003Cem\u003ECoccidioides immitis\u003C/em\u003E spherules\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranching filamentous hyphae\u003C/strong\u003E - This is characteristic of mould fungi like \u003Cem\u003EAspergillus\u003C/em\u003E species\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall oval yeast cells in chains\u003C/strong\u003E - This pattern is seen with some \u003Cem\u003ECandida\u003C/em\u003E species\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe polysaccharide capsule is the main virulence factor of \u003Cem\u003ECryptococcus neoformans\u003C/em\u003E, protecting it from phagocytosis and enabling its survival in the host. India ink staining is a rapid diagnostic technique that helps visualise this distinctive capsule.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cryptococcus neoformans is an encapsulated yeast that primarily infects immunocompromised patients","The polysaccharide capsule is the main virulence factor of Cryptococcus neoformans","India ink staining reveals the characteristic clear halo around cryptococcal cells due to capsule displacement"],"references":["Zhao Y, Ye L, Zhao F, Zhang L, Lu Z, Chu T, et al. Cryptococcus neoformans, a global threat to human health. Infectious Diseases of Poverty. 2023;12(1):20. Available at: https://idpjournal.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s40249-023-01073-4"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61111"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18538"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61111","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61111"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-30T12:16:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T12:17:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11270"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75593"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for